[This article leaves me with some concern. It does not tell us how
they know it is distemper. The clinical signs listed could just as
easily be rabies. There is no mention of how they know it is
distemper. While an odd gait and a ocular-nasal discharge may be
distemper, it may also be some other disease.

Residents should be urged to vaccinate their pets against rabies as
well as against distemper. Both diseases are very hard and distemper
is generally fatal in our animals while rabies is always fatal in our
animals and is fatal in humans if left untreated. - Mod.TG]

[The interactive HealthMap/ProMED map showing Troy, New York, is available at:
<http://healthmap.org/r/0jwc> - CopyEd.EJP]
